I agree with some of the other comments that several of the questions are posed in a way that doesn't allow for fully accurate answers. i.e.: I had suspicious symptoms early to mid March, but the question about possible previous symptoms asks only about the previous month (April), so I didn't report any of those symptoms. A number of the yes/no questions are tricky because the actual response is not so clear cut. i.e.: if someone has a pre-existing health condition, but still HAS to go to the grocery store, the answer to the question about a health condition making you stay home will be "no" (and these health conditions go unreported in the study). There are questions that would be better broken into 2 questions for more complete answers (i.e.: 1) Do you have a pre-existing health condition (specify); 2) Has this condition forced you to stay home). It concerns me that the cumulative data will be skewed because of this. (sorry devs, I'm not trying to be critical, but I worked as a field rep for the Census Bureau and have a lot of first hand experience with how the wording of questions affects data accuracy. When certain questions baffled a high percentage of respondents, we'd report it back to the statisticians writing the surveys so they could re-phrase)
